	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				O.K. Before I am beat up with the Plagerism Stick I want to give credit to all who have posted all the information reguarding this quest on this board. Praise to you all! I have endeavored to compile all the info I have on questing for the Trueshot Bow into this (hopefully) definiative refrence. Its rather lengthy, but should answer almost all your questions. Well here goes.........<BR>
<BR>
The Trueshot Bow quest is long and difficult, mostly because of the high fletching skill you need to finish the job (see the third from last paragraph). Start with the bag you get off the guild master, Maesyn Trueshot (grandson of its creator).<BR>
<BR>
Pruchase a few Small Lanterns and Flasks of Water where ever you faction with the local merchants are best. You will save money. If you are a Wood Elf or have the forage skill, save up you flasks of water. You will save even more coinage this way. The first note of caution (in a seemingly never ending string of them as yet to follow): Some foraged water comes in the form of Pods of Water. They look just like Flasks of Water graphically but are not the same thing! Furthermore, if you are not careful you will wind up drinking them. So make shure to have enough drink on your person.<BR>
First start out for Kaladim, city of the dwarves. Upon entering, turn right towards the bridge that crosses the underground river. Then take the tunnel on your left that goes to  North Kaladim. Head over to Everhot's Forge. Look around for Trantor Everhot Sometimes he's not there (wandering around the mines), but he usually returns soon. Hail him. Listen to his rantings and then reverse you direction back the way you entered. You are now lookng for Irontoe's Eats. When you return to the main entrance, this time turn left once you pass the entrance (as if you were entering again). It is the second building on your right (I think).  In there you will find Tumpy Irontoe tending bar. Hail him. Listen to his war storys and he will eventually tell you about his famous drink. Say &quot;I need a Tumpy Tonic&quot; or something to that effect. He will then tell you what you need to get him to create it. Now that you have character knowledge of this wonderous concoction, you may quest for it.<BR>
<BR>
Head to Freeport. There are two Jyle Windshots in this city. Be wary, the Jyle in the Seafarer's Roost (right by the docks) is an imposter. He wants a Faydark Champion's Tunic and 2gp. Here I lost my coveted tunic that I've been saveing as a momento. I felt rather gyped and almost gave up the quest then ans there. Then I found the other Jyle Windshot, upstairs in one of the rooms of the Hogcallers inn in West Freeport, Which is not far from the west gate. It si round the corner from the Freeport Malitia as a matter of fact. Ask him for &quot;Treant Wood&quot;. This Jyle wanted a small lantern (which you should of already had. don't worry they are easily obtainable). In exchange, he gives you the Treant Wood Shards, some faction, and some xp (unnoticable at my level). I'd suggest getting several because the boat ride is a long time spent twidling your thumbs (or trading languages).<BR>
If you dont want to make this long trip you can instead go to Kelethin . There is a merchant (sorry I can't remember his name) in Kelethin that sells wood shards for 7 silver a piece. (I bought some of these and used them in the bag trueshot gave me, on another fact finding atempt). I was able to combine all the items and get the treant stave with no problem! <BR>
Furthermoe, you also can get Treant Wood from Treants.  You know, those huge friendly tree looking things that move around the Karanas. If you kill them they drop Treant wood. But why any self respecting Rnager would kill one, and suffer the faction hit, is beyond me.<BR>
Now back to the quest at hand. You still need to go to the Sisterhood Island to get the Kiola Nuts for Tumpy Irontoe. Its just a matter of preference. Personally, if I am being forced to make the slow trip around the Ocean Of Tears just to grab some nuts, I'd at least want to stop in Freeport (to rest, sell my fletched arrows/bows, etc). But either way is fine.<BR>
<BR>
On the boat ride back from Freeport stop off at Sisterhood Island (it's the only stop in that direction), run to the nearest hut, the bigger of the three huts by the landing jetty. Turn left, sometimes the female vendor (I forget her name as well) is difficult to see behind the counter. I had looked in there twice before without seeing her. Buy a bunch of Kiola Nuts (like 8 of them) from the merchant. You need two for every dwarven wire you want to get. Unfortunately, they don't stack, so have plenty of backpacks. If you're quick, you can hop back on the boat before it leaves, otherwise you'll have a long wait ahead of you for the next boat. A word of caution. If you have no other food on your person. You WILL start to eat these! Make shure you have ample food for the trip (remember the Water Flasks!).<BR>
<BR>
Back ashore in Butcherblock, zone into Kaladim, turn left past the entrance and the second building on your right (I think) is Irontoe's bar (feeling de sha voo yet). Hail him. Work your way thu his ranting. Give him 1 Kiloa Nut and 1 Flask of Water and he'll give you 1 Trumpy Tonic. You need 2 tonics for every dwarven wire, so stock up. These do stack.<BR>
Next head back over to Everhot's Forge on the other side of Kaladim (you zone to get to it--look at the map in your book). Sometimes he's still not there (wandering around the mines), but he will usually return soon. Hail him. Give him 2 trumpy tonics (one each in separate slots!) and he'll give you a spool of dwarven wire, xp, and some faction. These are No Drop items. The wire spools also stack, but they will go into the bank, if put in a container. So I'd save getting the wire until you're already a master fletcher (or you have one lined up to do the job for you).<BR>
<BR>
Next stop is Steamfont. Kill the rogue clockworks (not the regular ones, the big spider ones) near the Mino Cave. These seem to drop the servos more often.  Destroying Rogue clockworks do not have any faction hit. Killing other clockworks does.  [I can't get into Ak'anon but that's because a merchant there has a thing against my diety.] These clockworks give on rare occasions micro servos (about a 1 in 5 shot I think..maybe worse). These are a No Drop item as well. They stack and you can put them in the bank as long as they are in a container. Yet another word of warning...a Minotaur Hero sometimes appears in the area. He will kill you if he sees you. Run to the windmills and the guard there will generally finish him off. (Be nice, and shout out a warning while you're running for your life.) He still cons red to me, but I will exact my revenge some day.<BR>
<BR>
The Spiderling Silk is the easiest component to get, you can be nice and buy it off the newbies, or spend more at the merchants (if you're feeling tired and lazy after all the running around), or just go kill the darn spiderlings yourself.  Yet another word of caution: I presume Spiderling Silks is different from spider silk, so watch for the slight difference in terms (kind of like how 'an orc warrior' is different from 'a orc warrior').<BR>
<BR>
Put ONE of each component into the bag and click combine and give the bag to Trueshot. He'll give you a Treant Bow Staff, xp, and faction. The staff is a lore item, so you can only have one (if you repeat and you already have one you do not get another and you lose the combined bag - very frustrateing indeed!). The staff can go into the bank. Caution:  Doing the quest again does not get you another Treant Staff until you've used it. Even if you keep it in the bank. <BR>
 <BR>
Now with all this done, hopefully you have a nice, high fletching skill because this bow is difficult to make. The lowest skill I've heard of with anyone successful at making the bow on the first try with a skill is 59. Yes 59!  I've heard someone with a 161 skill was successful 2 out of 7 tries. With a wisdom of 85, intelligence of 75 and a Fletching Skill Level of 150, I made it the first time. This is why you got extra components, right?<BR>
<BR>
To make the bow: the fletching kit can be bought at from merchant Lanin. the guy who sells arrow components (He is one platform noth of the Pod (Priest Of Discord) Lift platform in Kelethin). The planing tool can be bought off merchant Sylnis who (is by the wheelbarrow)  sells bow making items (she is on the same platform as the Trueshot Bow shop--too bad they don't sell their namesake). You must now get another micro servo and dwarven wire (which you already know how to get - which you should already have!). Put one of each component in the fletching kit to make the bow: 1 Treant wood bow staff, 1 Micro Serve, 1 Dwarven Wire and 1 Planing Tool  and click combine. With luck (and a few prayers to Tunare) you have a Trueshot Bow. Otherwise you have spare components (right?) If necessary, rinse and start over.<BR>
<BR>
This quest is quite time-consuming and the resulting item is marketable only to rangers, so it is rare to see a Trueshot Bow sold. I've heard one auctioned at 200 (in West Commons) or 300 - 500pp...don't know if it sold (in the Karanas) . <BR>
<BR>
The Trueshot Longbow's stats are as follows: <BR>
LORE ITEM. Wt 3.0 Rng 100  Del 45 Dam 20. Ranger ONLY item.<BR>
<BR>
There are stories about a 'second incarnation' of the trueshot that the guild master mentions when you complete the quest. I will cover that later on when I complete it. More then likely under the RAINCALLER (or whatever the bows name truly is) section of this message board - WHERE IT BELONGS!<BR>
Nuf said?<BR>
<BR>
Aullaiene, Ranger of Feydark's Champions. 13 seasons strong. Karana Server.<BR>
Have Mino-Axe, will tavel.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
